1
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:26,277
[ Wind Chimes Jingling ]

2
00:00:33,760 --> 00:00:36,069
[ Man Speaking Arabic ]

3
00:00:45,080 --> 00:00:48,152
[ Men Conversing ln Arabic ]

4
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:55,758
// [ Woman Singing
ln Hungarian ]

5
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:30,949
// [ Hungarian Song Ends ]

6
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,833
// [ Woman Vocalizing ]

7
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:36,190
[ Shouting ln German ]

8
00:03:36,280 --> 00:03:39,158
[ Shouting ]

9
00:03:47,080 --> 00:03:50,629
[ Engine Sputtering ]

10
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,276
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

11
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:21,716
- How are you ?
- Okay.

12
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:23,791
Your leg
will be fine.

13
00:04:23,880 --> 00:04:26,394
A lot of shrapnel came out.
I saved you the pieces.

14
00:04:26,520 --> 00:04:29,512
You are the prettiest girl
I've ever seen.

15
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:31,278
I don't think so.
Here.

16
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:34,790
- Would you kiss me ?
- No. I'll get you some tea.

17
00:04:34,920 --> 00:04:38,549
- It would mean such a lot to me.
- Would it ?

18
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:46,073
Thank you.

19
00:04:48,840 --> 00:04:51,718
- I can't sleep. Would you kiss me ?
- Oh.

20
00:04:51,840 --> 00:04:54,479
- You're so pretty.
- Will you tuck me in, please ?

21
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:57,239
[ Laughing ] Very funny.
Go to sleep now.

22
00:04:57,320 --> 00:05:00,153
- Where's the doctor ?
- Don't ask.

23
00:05:02,920 --> 00:05:06,435
[ Conversing ln Arabic ]

24
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:12,472
[ Conversation Continues ]

25
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:17,439
[ Gasping, Groaning ]

26
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:30,516
[ Breathing Heavily ]

27
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,591
[ Camel Grunts ]

28
00:05:43,240 --> 00:05:46,710
[ Man Breathing Heavily ]

29
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:51,951
[ Fly Buzzing ]

30
00:05:52,040 --> 00:05:55,510
[ Gasping, Gagging ]

31
00:06:04,360 --> 00:06:07,272
[ Chattering ]

32
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:12,397
[ Indistinct Conversations ]

33
00:06:18,120 --> 00:06:21,396
God, I hate giving blood.
Can't stand needles.

34
00:06:27,680 --> 00:06:30,433
Is there anybody
from Picton ?

35
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:33,438
Picton ?
I don't know.

36
00:06:33,520 --> 00:06:37,354
I'd like to see somebody
from home before I go.

37
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:47,518
- Do we have anybody from Picton ?
- Why Picton ?

38
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:50,239
He's from there. Edge of Lake Ontario,
right, soldier ?

39
00:06:50,320 --> 00:06:53,710
That's where your sweetie's from,
isn't it ? Around there ?

40
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:56,360
Ask him what company
he's with.

41
00:06:56,480 --> 00:07:00,393
- Third Canadian Fusiliers.
- Third Canadian Fusiliers.

42
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:05,390
Does he know
Captain McGan ?

43
00:07:05,480 --> 00:07:09,758
He bought it yesterday.
Shot to bits.

44
00:07:09,840 --> 00:07:12,274
- What did he say ?
- Doesn't know him.

45
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:14,510
[ Shell Whistles, Explodes ]

46
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:16,716
Hana, get down !

47
00:07:16,840 --> 00:07:20,958
[ Screaming, Shouting ]

48
00:07:21,080 --> 00:07:24,072
[ Sobbing ]
He's dead. He's dead.

49
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:25,997
[ Shouting ]

50
00:07:26,120 --> 00:07:29,078
[ Sobbing ]
He's dead.

51
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:30,991
He's dead.

52
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:33,992
[ Explosions ]

53
00:07:37,080 --> 00:07:40,152
[ Bottles Clinking ]

54
00:07:45,960 --> 00:07:49,316
[ Conversing ln Arabic ]

55
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:01,756
[ Arabic ]

56
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:08,755
[ Breathing Heavily ]

57
00:08:08,840 --> 00:08:11,513
[ Chanting ]

58
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:14,279
[ Continues ]

59
00:08:16,200 --> 00:08:19,351
[ Chanting Continues,
Drumbeat ]

60
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:21,596
[ Arabic ]

61
00:08:21,680 --> 00:08:25,036
[ Chanting Continues ]

62
00:08:25,160 --> 00:08:27,435
[ Breathing Heavily ]

63
00:08:44,840 --> 00:08:48,276
[ Chattering ]

64
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:54,790
[ Man ]
Name, rank, serial number ?

65
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:56,797
[ Man #2 ]
No, sorry.

66
00:08:56,880 --> 00:08:59,440
I think I was
a pilot.

67
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:02,950
I was found in the wreckage of a plane
at the beginning of the war.

68
00:09:03,080 --> 00:09:04,877
Can you remember
where you were born ?

69
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:07,514
Am I being interrogated ?

70
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:11,195
You should be trying to
trick me, make me speak German.

71
00:09:11,320 --> 00:09:13,515
- Which I can, by the way.
- Why ?

72
00:09:13,640 --> 00:09:16,200
- Are you German ?
- No.

73
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:19,949
How do you know you're not German
if you don't remember anything ?

74
00:09:20,040 --> 00:09:22,600
Might-- Might I have
a sip of water ?

75
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:29,709
[ Sea Gulls Calling ]

76
00:09:29,800 --> 00:09:31,870
[ Gulps ]

77
00:09:34,200 --> 00:09:36,156
- Thank you.
- It's okay.

78
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:40,235
I remember
lots of things.

79
00:09:40,360 --> 00:09:44,592
I remember her garden,
plunging down to the sea.

80
00:09:44,680 --> 00:09:47,911
- Nothing between you and France.
- This was your garden ?

81
00:09:48,040 --> 00:09:50,793
- Or my wife's.
- You were married then ?

82
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:55,038
I think so. Although I believe that
to be true of a number of Germans.

83
00:09:57,200 --> 00:09:59,031
Look.

84
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:02,669
[ Gasping ]
I have this much lung.

85
00:10:02,760 --> 00:10:05,069
The rest of my organs
are packing up.

86
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:08,357
What could it possibly matter
if I'm a Tutankhamen ?

87
00:10:08,480 --> 00:10:12,234
I'm a bit of...
toast, my friend.

88
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:15,716
Sorry I can't help you.

89
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,958
[ Horn Honking ]

90
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:29,437
[ Breathing Heavily ]

91
00:10:29,520 --> 00:10:31,590
Are you all right ?

92
00:10:31,720 --> 00:10:34,553
I know you hate to be moved.
I'm sorry.

93
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:40,952
- [ Honking ]
- Hana !

94
00:10:41,080 --> 00:10:44,311
- Jan ?
- Hana !

95
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:48,075
There's meant to be lace in the next
village. The boys are gonna take me.

96
00:10:48,200 --> 00:10:50,395
- You don't have any money, do ya ?
- No.

97
00:10:50,520 --> 00:10:52,158
- Just in case there's a sale.
- No.

98
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:53,753
Hana, I know you do.
Come on.

99
00:10:53,840 --> 00:10:55,353
- No !
- Oh, come on.

100
00:10:55,440 --> 00:10:57,829
I swear to God,
this'll be the last time. I swear.

101
00:10:57,960 --> 00:11:00,349
She's a softie.
She loves me.

102
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:05,598
- I'll pay you back ! I promise !
- [ Laughing ]

103
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:08,439
I'm not sewing
anything else for you.

104
00:11:08,520 --> 00:11:10,636
I love you !

105
00:11:10,760 --> 00:11:13,797
Whoa !
Pienza, boys !

106
00:11:18,440 --> 00:11:20,317
[ Breathing Heavily ]

107
00:11:30,480 --> 00:11:32,311
[ Man ] Get some water
over here !

108
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:36,313
Jan !
Oh, no !

109
00:11:37,760 --> 00:11:40,638
Hana, where're
you going ?

110
00:11:40,720 --> 00:11:43,837
- Stay back !
- Stop, Hana !

111
00:11:44,920 --> 00:11:47,992
- Stay--
- [ Crying ]

112
00:11:51,320 --> 00:11:53,436
No !

113
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:55,994
No !

114
00:12:38,600 --> 00:12:41,398
- Hey ! Hey !
- Don't move !

115
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:43,357
Don't move !
Don't move !

116
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:45,590
Stand absolutely still !

117
00:12:45,680 --> 00:12:48,274
You're walking in
a mine field !

118
00:12:50,920 --> 00:12:53,229
Good.

119
00:12:53,320 --> 00:12:55,993
That's good.

120
00:12:56,120 --> 00:12:59,078
Just stay still
for me...

121
00:12:59,200 --> 00:13:01,316
and we'll be fine.

122
00:13:03,080 --> 00:13:05,230
What are you doing ?

123
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:08,312
What the bloody hell do
you think you're doing ?

124
00:13:09,480 --> 00:13:12,233
[ Hana ]
It's Jan's.

125
00:13:13,480 --> 00:13:15,994
[ Sighs ]

126
00:13:38,480 --> 00:13:41,438
[ Hana ] Are you in pain ?
Do you need something ?

127
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:43,351
- Yes.
- Okay.

128
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:47,594
Are you okay ?

129
00:13:47,720 --> 00:13:50,792
- You and Jan were--
- We keep moving him
in and out of the truck.

130
00:13:50,920 --> 00:13:53,832
Why ? He's dying.
What's the point ?

131
00:13:53,960 --> 00:13:56,394
We can hardly leave him.
Do you mean leave him ?

132
00:13:56,520 --> 00:13:58,954
No, no,
I don't mean leave him.

133
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:10,396
This will help you.

134
00:14:12,200 --> 00:14:14,509
I must be a curse.

135
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:17,956
Anybody who loves me...
[ Sighs ]

136
00:14:19,080 --> 00:14:21,753
anybody who gets
close to me--

137
00:14:23,080 --> 00:14:25,116
Oh, I must be cursed.

138
00:14:30,320 --> 00:14:32,151
Which is it ?

139
00:15:25,920 --> 00:15:28,195
// [ Single Piano Key Plays ]

140
00:15:36,360 --> 00:15:38,237
[ Grunts ]

141
00:15:54,840 --> 00:15:58,549
- When he dies, I'll catch up.
- It's not safe here.

142
00:15:58,640 --> 00:16:02,235
The whole country's crawling with
bandits and Germans and God knows what.

143
00:16:02,320 --> 00:16:04,629
- It's madness ! I can't allow it.
- The war is over.

144
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:06,557
How can it be
desertion ?

145
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:09,831
It's not over everywhere.
I didn't mean literally.

146
00:16:09,960 --> 00:16:12,793
This is normal, a shock,
for all of us, Hana.

147
00:16:12,920 --> 00:16:16,151
I need morphine, a lot.
And a pistol.

148
00:16:20,800 --> 00:16:23,837
If anything ever happened to you,
I'd never forgive myself.

149
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,439
We're heading
for Leghorn.

150
00:16:29,560 --> 00:16:31,676
"Livorno,"
the ltalians call it.

151
00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:34,394
We'll expect you.

152
00:16:43,200 --> 00:16:44,997
Fine.

153
00:16:51,080 --> 00:16:53,355
- Thank you.
- You're welcome, ma'am.

154
00:16:56,520 --> 00:16:59,273
- Oh, Hana.
- I'll be okay.

155
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:02,233
I'll catch up.
Good.

156
00:17:09,800 --> 00:17:12,360
[ Sighs ]

157
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:17,553
[ Muttering Song Lyrics ]

158
00:17:17,640 --> 00:17:20,313
[ Continues ]

159
00:17:31,880 --> 00:17:35,156
[ Engines Droning ]

160
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:56,036
[ Grunting ]

161
00:18:05,800 --> 00:18:08,598
What-- What was
all that banging ?

162
00:18:08,680 --> 00:18:13,117
Are you-- Are you fighting rats,
or the entire German army ?

163
00:18:14,280 --> 00:18:18,353
No. I was repairing
the stairs.

164
00:18:18,440 --> 00:18:22,513
I found a library,
and the books were very useful.

165
00:18:22,600 --> 00:18:25,797
Before you find too many
uses for those books,

166
00:18:25,920 --> 00:18:28,229
you might
read some to me.

167
00:18:28,360 --> 00:18:30,794
I think they're all in ltalian,
but I'll look, yes.

168
00:18:30,920 --> 00:18:33,434
- What about your own book ?
- My book ?

169
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:36,478
Oh, yes,
the Herodotus.

170
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:39,393
Yes, you can read him.

171
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,353
Oh. I found plums.

172
00:18:42,440 --> 00:18:46,035
We have plums
in the orchard. There.

173
00:18:46,120 --> 00:18:48,793
We have an orchard.

174
00:18:48,880 --> 00:18:52,793
Herodotus is
the father of history.

175
00:18:52,880 --> 00:18:55,440
- Do you know that ?
- I don't know anything.

176
00:19:05,400 --> 00:19:07,197
Hmm.

177
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:17,116
It's a--

178
00:19:17,240 --> 00:19:20,312
It's a very plum...

179
00:19:20,440 --> 00:19:22,237
plum.

180
00:20:08,640 --> 00:20:10,073
[ Thud ]

181
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:14,399
[ Man Speaking Arabic ]

182
00:20:14,520 --> 00:20:18,399
[ Responds ln Arabic ]

183
00:20:39,560 --> 00:20:42,028
[ Arabic ]

184
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:48,156
A mountain the shape
of a woman's back. Good, good.

185
00:21:11,320 --> 00:21:14,676
- Hello, Geoffrey !
- Madox, hello !

186
00:21:14,760 --> 00:21:18,036
- Welcome to the expedition.
- How do you do ? Geoffrey Clifton.

187
00:21:18,120 --> 00:21:19,473
Splendid to finally
meet you all.

188
00:21:19,560 --> 00:21:21,391
This is Dante D'Agostino
and Diggy Bermann, our archaeologist.

189
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:23,755
- Beautiful plane.
- This is Sharif AI Fouad, Egyptologist.

190
00:21:23,880 --> 00:21:26,678
- And this is my wife, Katharine.
- Hello.

191
00:21:26,760 --> 00:21:28,591
We're your
new apprentices.

192
00:21:28,680 --> 00:21:31,035
-Welcome to the lnternational Sand Club.
-[ Laughing ]

193
00:21:31,120 --> 00:21:34,715
- To the lnternational Sand Club.
- I'll get cups.

194
00:21:34,840 --> 00:21:37,115
- Marvellous plane. Did you look ?
- Yes.

195
00:21:37,240 --> 00:21:40,152
Isn't it ? A wedding present
from Katharine's parents.

196
00:21:40,240 --> 00:21:42,196
We're calling it
Rupert Bear.

197
00:21:42,280 --> 00:21:44,555
- Hello. Geoffrey Clifton.
- Almasy.

198
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:47,831
We can finally consign my old bird
to the scrap heap.

199
00:21:47,960 --> 00:21:50,315
Mrs Clifton,
I'd like to present...

200
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:53,193
- Count Almasy.
- Hello.

201
00:21:53,320 --> 00:21:55,993
Geoffrey gave me your monograph
and I was reading up in the desert.

202
00:21:56,080 --> 00:21:58,548
- Very impressive.
- Thank you.

203
00:21:58,640 --> 00:22:01,871
I wanted to meet the man who could write
a long paper with so few adjectives.

204
00:22:01,960 --> 00:22:05,748
Well, a thing is still a thing,
no matter what you place in front of it.

205
00:22:05,880 --> 00:22:09,589
Big car, slow car,
chauffeur-driven car.

206
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:12,473
- [ Madox ] Broken car.
- It's still a car.

207
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:15,677
- Not much use, though.
- [ Katharine ] Love ?

208
00:22:15,800 --> 00:22:19,315
Romantic love,
plutonic love, filial love.

209
00:22:19,400 --> 00:22:21,709
- Quite different things, surely.
- Uxoriousness.

210
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:26,078
That's my favourite kind of love.
Excessive love of one's wife.

211
00:22:26,200 --> 00:22:29,829
- Now there you have me.
- [ Men Laughing ]

212
00:22:29,960 --> 00:22:32,394
- They're tourists.
- Absolute rot.

213
00:22:32,520 --> 00:22:34,829
They're highly recommended
by the Royal Geographic Society.

214
00:22:34,920 --> 00:22:36,797
She's charming and
has read everything.

215
00:22:36,920 --> 00:22:39,593
- He's meant to be a ruddy good flier.
- We don't need another pilot.

216
00:22:39,720 --> 00:22:41,597
He can make aerial maps
of the whole route.

217
00:22:41,680 --> 00:22:44,240
You can't explore
from the air, Madox.

218
00:22:44,360 --> 00:22:47,113
If you could explore from the air,
life would be very simple.

219
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:49,519
Contact.

220
00:22:51,600 --> 00:22:53,431
Contact.

221
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:09,435
I should try
and move the bed.

222
00:24:09,520 --> 00:24:11,875
I want you to be able
to see the view.

223
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:15,037
It's good. It's a view
from a monastery.

224
00:24:15,160 --> 00:24:18,436
- I can already see.
- How ?

225
00:24:18,560 --> 00:24:21,120
- How can you see anything ?
- No, no, not the window.

226
00:24:21,240 --> 00:24:23,800
I can't bear
the light anyway.

227
00:24:23,880 --> 00:24:26,235
I can see all the way
to the desert.

228
00:24:26,320 --> 00:24:28,151
I'm turning you.

229
00:24:28,240 --> 00:24:31,437
Exploring before the war,
making maps.

230
00:24:31,560 --> 00:24:34,552
Is there sand in my eyes ?
Are you cleaning sand from my ears ?

231
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:38,070
No sand.
That's your morphine speaking.

232
00:24:45,040 --> 00:24:47,998
I can see my wife
in that view.

233
00:24:50,440 --> 00:24:53,273
Are you
remembering more ?

234
00:24:53,360 --> 00:24:56,397
- Could I have a cigarette ?
- Are you crazy ?

235
00:24:57,760 --> 00:25:00,399
[ Coughing ]

236
00:25:00,520 --> 00:25:05,036
Why-- Why are you so determined
to keep me alive ?

237
00:25:05,160 --> 00:25:08,436
[ Sighs ]
Because I'm a nurse.

238
00:25:33,320 --> 00:25:36,232
[ Sound Of Hana's Feet
Hopping ]

239
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:39,193
[ Drumbeats, Chanting ]

240
00:25:39,280 --> 00:25:41,714
[ Continues ]

241
00:25:47,880 --> 00:25:51,634
// [ Arabic ]

242
00:25:55,320 --> 00:25:56,719
Bravo.

243
00:25:56,840 --> 00:25:59,274
/ We have an
old-fashioned tomato /

244
00:25:59,400 --> 00:26:01,595
/ A Long lsland potato /

245
00:26:01,720 --> 00:26:04,712
/ But yes
We have no bananas /

246
00:26:04,840 --> 00:26:06,956
/ We have no bananas today //

247
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:10,629
// [ Arabic ]

248
00:26:10,760 --> 00:26:14,036
// [ German ]

249
00:26:14,120 --> 00:26:15,951
// [ Italian ]

250
00:26:16,040 --> 00:26:19,316
// [ Arabic ]

251
00:26:19,400 --> 00:26:21,231
- Next !
- Katharine !

252
00:26:21,440 --> 00:26:24,159
[ Hana ] "The King insisted that
he would find some way...

253
00:26:24,240 --> 00:26:26,117
"to prove beyond dispute...

254
00:26:26,240 --> 00:26:30,153
"that his wife
was fairest of all women.

255
00:26:30,280 --> 00:26:33,716
"'l will hide you in your room
where we sleep,' said Candaules--

256
00:26:33,800 --> 00:26:36,268
- said Candaules."
- Candaules.

257
00:26:36,360 --> 00:26:38,828
"Candaules."

258
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:40,956
Candaules.

259
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:44,868
Candaules tells Gyges that the Queen has
the same practise every night.

260
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:47,798
She takes off
her clothes...

261
00:26:47,880 --> 00:26:51,634
and puts them on the chair
by the door to her room.

262
00:26:51,720 --> 00:26:54,075
"'And from where you stand,

263
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:57,516
you will be able to gaze
on her at your leisure."'

264
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:02,310
And that evening, it's exactly as
the King has told him.

265
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:04,237
She goes
to the chair,

266
00:27:04,360 --> 00:27:06,351
removes her clothes
one by one,

267
00:27:06,440 --> 00:27:10,274
until she's standing naked
in full view of Gyges.

268
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:14,837
And indeed, she was more lovely
than he could have imagined.

269
00:27:14,920 --> 00:27:18,356
But then,
the Queen looked up...

270
00:27:18,440 --> 00:27:22,399
and saw Gyges concealed
in the shadows.

271
00:27:22,480 --> 00:27:24,948
And although she said
nothing, she shuddered.

272
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:32,950
And the next day,

273
00:27:33,080 --> 00:27:36,629
she sends for, for Gyges
and challenged him.

274
00:27:36,720 --> 00:27:40,918
- And hearing his story,
this is what she said.
- Off with his head !

275
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:42,718
[ Laughing ]

276
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:47,912
She said, "Either you
must submit to death...

277
00:27:48,040 --> 00:27:50,793
"for gazing on that
which you should not,

278
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:53,275
"or else kill my husband
who has shamed me...

279
00:27:55,120 --> 00:27:58,078
and become King
in his place."

280
00:28:00,200 --> 00:28:02,714
So Gyges kills the King,

281
00:28:02,800 --> 00:28:06,713
marries the Queen and becomes ruler
of Lydia for 28 years.

282
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:10,477
The end.

283
00:28:13,040 --> 00:28:15,634
Shall I spin
the bottle ?

284
00:28:15,720 --> 00:28:18,188
[ Madox ] So, Geoffrey,
let that be a lesson to you.

285
00:28:18,280 --> 00:28:20,589
- [ Katharine ] D'Agostino !
- D'Agostino !

286
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:24,075
Are you asleep ?

287
00:28:25,160 --> 00:28:27,594
Yes.

288
00:28:27,720 --> 00:28:30,757
No. I'm dropping off.

289
00:29:09,720 --> 00:29:11,517
[ Cawing ]

290
00:29:11,640 --> 00:29:14,359
Go away !

291
00:29:14,440 --> 00:29:16,954
Go ! Go !

292
00:29:26,520 --> 00:29:28,317
[ Grunts ]

293
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:32,951
Buon giorno.

294
00:29:34,160 --> 00:29:36,958
- Hana ?
- What do you want ?

295
00:29:37,040 --> 00:29:39,838
I met your
friend Mary.

296
00:29:39,960 --> 00:29:43,032
She said I should stop and see
if you were all right.

297
00:29:43,120 --> 00:29:47,671
Apparently we're neighbours. My house
is two blocks from yours in Montreal.

298
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:50,360
Cabot,
north of Laurier.

299
00:29:50,440 --> 00:29:53,159
- Bonjour.
- Bonjour.

300
00:29:55,440 --> 00:29:57,351
For you.

301
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:59,516
I'd like to take credit for it,
but it's from Mary.

302
00:29:59,600 --> 00:30:03,036
My name is David Caravaggio,
but nobody ever called me David.

303
00:30:03,160 --> 00:30:07,517
Caravaggio they find
too absurd to miss out on.

304
00:30:07,600 --> 00:30:09,192
Oh !

305
00:30:09,320 --> 00:30:11,629
[ Snickers ]
Oh !

306
00:30:11,720 --> 00:30:13,836
Oh, shit.
Stupid hands.

307
00:30:13,960 --> 00:30:17,111
Let me do that.

308
00:30:22,720 --> 00:30:25,234
They're fresh.

309
00:30:25,320 --> 00:30:27,629
I haven't had
an egg in--

310
00:30:30,040 --> 00:30:32,429
Have you noticed
there are chickens ?

311
00:30:32,520 --> 00:30:34,590
In ltaly, you get chickens
but no eggs.

312
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:37,359
In Africa, they're always eggs
but never chickens.

313
00:30:37,480 --> 00:30:40,711
- Who's separating them ?
- You were in Africa ?

314
00:30:40,840 --> 00:30:42,558
Yes, I was.

315
00:30:42,680 --> 00:30:45,433
So was my patient.

316
00:30:45,560 --> 00:30:48,438
Look, I'd like to
stay for a while.

317
00:30:48,520 --> 00:30:50,351
I have to do
some work here.

318
00:30:50,440 --> 00:30:53,671
I speak the language.
There are partisans to be disarmed.

319
00:30:53,800 --> 00:30:57,395
We embrace them and see
if we can relieve them of their weapons,

320
00:30:57,480 --> 00:30:59,436
you know,
while we hide.

321
00:30:59,560 --> 00:31:02,916
I was a thief, so the army
thought I'd be good at it.

322
00:31:03,040 --> 00:31:05,679
- So you can shoot a pistol ?
- No.

323
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:08,473
Do you have a problem
with those ?

324
00:31:10,280 --> 00:31:11,633
No.

325
00:31:11,720 --> 00:31:14,234
- I should look at them before you go.
- Look.

326
00:31:14,320 --> 00:31:16,595
It's a big place.
We needn't disturb each other.

327
00:31:16,680 --> 00:31:18,830
I'll sleep
in the stable.

328
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:20,876
It doesn't matter where I sleep.
I don't sleep.

329
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:23,912
I don't know what Mary told you
about me, but I don't need company.

330
00:31:24,040 --> 00:31:26,918
I don't need
to be looked after.

331
00:31:30,960 --> 00:31:34,032
There is a man
downstairs.

332
00:31:34,120 --> 00:31:37,351
He brought us eggs.
He might stay.

333
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:40,153
Why ?
Can he lay eggs ?

334
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:42,236
He's Canadian.

335
00:31:42,360 --> 00:31:46,194
Why are people always so happy when they
collide with one from the same place ?

336
00:31:46,280 --> 00:31:49,033
What happened in Montreal
when you passed a man in the street ?

337
00:31:49,160 --> 00:31:52,072
Did you invite him
to live with you ?

338
00:31:53,480 --> 00:31:55,630
He needn't
disturb you.

339
00:31:55,720 --> 00:31:58,154
He can't.
I'm already disturbed.

340
00:31:58,280 --> 00:32:00,919
[ Sighs ]

341
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:04,709
There's a war. Where you come from
becomes important.

342
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:08,196
[ Patient ]
Why ? I hate that idea.

343
00:32:13,160 --> 00:32:15,993
Ah !
It's gonna work.

344
00:32:17,040 --> 00:32:19,508
Gently.

345
00:32:19,600 --> 00:32:22,273
[ Knocking ]

346
00:32:23,440 --> 00:32:25,271
Can I help ?

347
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:27,191
It's finished.

348
00:32:27,280 --> 00:32:29,396
So, you're our
Canadian pickpocket ?

349
00:32:29,480 --> 00:32:31,994
Thief I think
is more accurate.

350
00:32:32,120 --> 00:32:36,477
I understand you were in Africa.
Whereabouts ?

351
00:32:36,600 --> 00:32:39,068
Oh, all over.

352
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:42,272
All over ?

353
00:32:42,400 --> 00:32:45,756
I kept trying to cover
a very modest portion and still failed.

354
00:32:45,840 --> 00:32:48,638
- Are you leaving us ?
- Yes.

355
00:32:48,720 --> 00:32:51,154
Now's our opportunity
to swap war wounds.

356
00:32:51,240 --> 00:32:54,391
[ Laughs ]
Then I'm definitely going.

357
00:32:57,880 --> 00:33:00,553
Does she have
war wounds ?

358
00:33:00,680 --> 00:33:02,716
I think anybody
she ever loves...

359
00:33:02,840 --> 00:33:05,035
tends to die on her.

360
00:33:05,160 --> 00:33:07,993
- Are you planning to be the exception ?
- Me ?

361
00:33:08,120 --> 00:33:10,236
[ Laughs ]
I think you've got...

362
00:33:10,360 --> 00:33:12,555
the wrong end
of the stick, old boy.

363
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:14,477
So...

364
00:33:15,400 --> 00:33:17,197
Caravaggio.

365
00:33:17,320 --> 00:33:20,392
Hana thinks
you invented your name.

366
00:33:20,520 --> 00:33:22,954
And you've
forgotten yours.

367
00:33:23,080 --> 00:33:27,949
I said that no one would ever invent
such a preposterous name.

368
00:33:28,040 --> 00:33:30,235
And I said you can
forget everything,

369
00:33:31,760 --> 00:33:34,558
but you never forget
your name.

370
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:36,955
Count Almasy.

371
00:33:37,040 --> 00:33:39,235
That name mean
anything to you ?

372
00:33:39,360 --> 00:33:41,590
Or Katharine Clifton ?

373
00:33:41,680 --> 00:33:44,478
[ People Chattering ]

374
00:33:49,880 --> 00:33:51,677
Oh, I'm sorry.

375
00:33:51,800 --> 00:33:54,792
- How much did you pay ?
- Oh, hello.

376
00:33:54,920 --> 00:33:58,595
They don't see foreign women
in this market. How much did you pay ?

377
00:33:58,720 --> 00:34:01,280
Um, 7, 8 pounds,
I suppose.

378
00:34:01,360 --> 00:34:03,669
- Which store ?
- Why ?

379
00:34:03,760 --> 00:34:06,957
You've been cheated.
Oh, don't worry, we'll take it back.

380
00:34:07,080 --> 00:34:08,877
I don't want
to take it back.

381
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:12,037
- This is not worth 8 pounds.
- It is to me.

382
00:34:12,160 --> 00:34:14,515
- Did you bargain ?
- I don't care to bargain.

383
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:16,670
That insults them.

384
00:34:18,280 --> 00:34:21,750
I don't believe that. I think
that you're insulted by me somehow.

385
00:34:21,840 --> 00:34:25,071
I'd be very happy to obtain
the correct price for this.

386
00:34:25,160 --> 00:34:27,674
I apologize
if I appear abrupt.

387
00:34:27,800 --> 00:34:30,075
I'm rusty at social graces.

388
00:34:34,400 --> 00:34:36,277
How do you find Cairo ?

389
00:34:36,360 --> 00:34:39,989
- Did you visit the pyramids ?
- Excuse me.

390
00:34:40,080 --> 00:34:42,640
Or the Sphinx ?

391
00:34:45,760 --> 00:34:49,912
[ Almasy ] Latitude, 25, 33.
Longitude, 25, 16.

392
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,754
We attempt to drive northeast of Kofer,
we'll leave our bones in the desert.

393
00:34:53,840 --> 00:34:56,149
- I disagree.
- You're Hungarian. You always disagree.

394
00:34:56,240 --> 00:34:58,196
- Good evening, gentlemen.
- Good evening.

395
00:34:58,320 --> 00:35:00,276
- How is your charming wife ?
- Marvellous.

396
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:02,550
She's in love
with the hotel plumbing.

397
00:35:02,640 --> 00:35:04,676
She's either in the swimming pool.
She swims for hours.

398
00:35:04,760 --> 00:35:07,513
She's a fish. It's quite incredible.
Or she's in the bath.

399
00:35:07,600 --> 00:35:10,592
- [ Laughing ]
- Actually, she's just outside.

400
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:14,116
Chaps only
in the Long Bar.

401
00:35:18,400 --> 00:35:20,197
Mrs Clifton.

402
00:35:20,320 --> 00:35:24,598
You'll have to forgive us. We're not
accustomed to the company of women.

403
00:35:24,720 --> 00:35:28,190
Not at all. I was thoroughly
enjoying my book.

404
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:31,039
- The team is in mourning, darling.
- Oh, really ?

405
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:34,271
I'm afraid we're not having much luck
obtaining funds for the expedition.

406
00:35:34,400 --> 00:35:36,197
Oh. Well, what'll you do ?

407
00:35:36,320 --> 00:35:38,595
More modest expedition,
or even wait a year.

408
00:35:38,720 --> 00:35:41,553
- It's a disaster.
- Remind our families we still exist.

409
00:35:41,680 --> 00:35:43,557
Good heavens,
are you married, Madox ?

410
00:35:43,640 --> 00:35:46,598
Very much so.
We all are.

411
00:35:46,680 --> 00:35:48,989
- Save my friend Almasy here.
- I feel much better.

412
00:35:49,080 --> 00:35:52,675
Don't you, darling ?
We were feeling rather self-conscious.

413
00:35:52,760 --> 00:35:54,751
Let's toast, then.
Absent wives.

414
00:35:54,840 --> 00:35:57,434
- [ All ] Absent wives.
- And present ones.

415
00:35:57,520 --> 00:35:59,078
And future ones.

416
00:36:02,680 --> 00:36:05,478
// [ Jazz ]

417
00:36:16,720 --> 00:36:19,234
// [ Song Ends ]

418
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:21,151
Thank you.

419
00:36:21,240 --> 00:36:23,879
Excuse me.
May I ?

420
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:26,753
// [ Slow ]

421
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:41,197
- Why did you follow me yesterday ?
- I'm sorry. What ?

422
00:36:41,320 --> 00:36:43,754
After the market,
you followed me to the hotel.

423
00:36:43,880 --> 00:36:47,793
I was concerned. A woman
in that part of Cairo, a European woman.

424
00:36:47,920 --> 00:36:50,275
- I felt obliged to.
- You felt obliged to ?

425
00:36:50,360 --> 00:36:53,079
As the wife of
one of our party.

426
00:36:53,200 --> 00:36:56,078
So why follow me ?
Escort me, by all means.

427
00:36:56,200 --> 00:36:59,272
But following me
is predatory, isn't it ?

428
00:37:37,120 --> 00:37:40,237
[ Snoring ]

429
00:37:40,360 --> 00:37:43,238
Could I ask you
to move ?

430
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:46,311
I'm sorry,
but l--

431
00:37:48,080 --> 00:37:50,913
I'm sorry.
Of course.

432
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:53,798
- It's just when you move.
- It was too rude of me.

433
00:37:53,880 --> 00:37:58,271
- I can't really bear the pressure--
- Are you all right ?

434
00:37:58,360 --> 00:38:00,555
I was dreaming.
Awful.

435
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:39,393
[ Crying ]

436
00:38:45,840 --> 00:38:49,196
[ Sobbing ]

437
00:38:49,320 --> 00:38:51,117
Hana.

438
00:38:53,760 --> 00:38:57,150
Hana, are you
all right ?

439
00:38:57,280 --> 00:38:59,714
Leave me alone.

440
00:39:01,040 --> 00:39:02,871
[ Sobs ]

441
00:39:19,960 --> 00:39:22,076
You're in love with him,
aren't you ?

442
00:39:22,160 --> 00:39:25,118
Your poor patient.

443
00:39:25,200 --> 00:39:27,998
You think he's a saint
because of the way he looks.

444
00:39:28,080 --> 00:39:31,038
I don't think he is.

445
00:39:31,120 --> 00:39:33,270
I'm not so
in love with him.

446
00:39:33,360 --> 00:39:37,478
I'm in love with ghosts.

447
00:39:37,600 --> 00:39:40,512
So is he.
He's in love with ghosts.

448
00:39:40,600 --> 00:39:42,750
What if I told you
he did this to me ?

449
00:39:45,880 --> 00:39:48,997
How could he have ?
When ?

450
00:39:49,120 --> 00:39:51,554
I'm one of his ghosts,
and he wouldn't even know it.

451
00:39:51,640 --> 00:39:55,315
- I don't know what that means.
- Ask your saint who he is.

452
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:58,516
Ask him
who he's killed.

453
00:40:01,760 --> 00:40:05,958
[ Sobbing ] Please, don't creep
around this house.

454
00:40:06,080 --> 00:40:08,310
See, I don't think
he's forgotten anything !

455
00:40:08,400 --> 00:40:11,153
I think he wants to forget !

456
00:40:13,040 --> 00:40:15,190
[ Clifton ]
Gentlemen, to mapmaking.

457
00:40:15,280 --> 00:40:17,111
[ All ]
To mapmaking !

458
00:40:17,200 --> 00:40:19,430
And a special thank you
to Geoffrey and Katharine,

459
00:40:19,560 --> 00:40:23,553
without whose fund-raising heroics,
we'd still be kicking our heels.

460
00:40:23,640 --> 00:40:25,949
- To arm-twisting.
- [ All ] Arm-twisting.

461
00:40:26,040 --> 00:40:29,953
Did Katharine say Geoffrey
has to fly back to Cairo ?

462
00:40:30,040 --> 00:40:32,679
Return the favour.
Take a few photographs for the army.

463
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:35,035
Oh, um, what kind
of photographs ?

464
00:40:35,120 --> 00:40:36,951
Portraits.

465
00:40:37,040 --> 00:40:39,395
The brigadier,
the brigadier's wife,

466
00:40:39,480 --> 00:40:43,314
the brigadier's dog, brigadier
by the pyramids, brigadier breathing.

467
00:40:43,440 --> 00:40:45,795
And I shall,
of course, be bereft.

468
00:40:45,880 --> 00:40:48,553
I'll finally be able to
explore the Cairo nightlife.

469
00:40:48,680 --> 00:40:51,433
I shall produce an authoritative guide
to the zinc bars and--

470
00:40:51,560 --> 00:40:54,120
I want to say hareems. Are we
in the right country for hareems ?

471
00:40:54,240 --> 00:40:56,037
[ Madox ]
Harems.

472
00:41:01,040 --> 00:41:03,429
- Bye, my love.
- Travel safe.

473
00:41:03,560 --> 00:41:05,676
Catch up
in a week.

474
00:41:08,240 --> 00:41:11,391
Clifton,
safe journey.

475
00:41:11,480 --> 00:41:15,553
You too. Good luck.
Glad the funds have turned up.

476
00:41:15,640 --> 00:41:18,438
Clifton.

477
00:41:21,520 --> 00:41:23,954
This is probably
none of my business.

478
00:41:24,080 --> 00:41:26,753
Your wife.

479
00:41:26,840 --> 00:41:29,957
- Think it's appropriate to leave her ?
- Appropriate ?

480
00:41:30,080 --> 00:41:33,629
Well, the desert is, it's, uh--
for a woman, it's very tough.

481
00:41:33,760 --> 00:41:35,876
I wonder if it's
not too much for her.

482
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:38,355
Are you mad ? Katharine loves it here.
She told me yesterday.

483
00:41:38,480 --> 00:41:41,313
- All the same, were I you--
- I've known Katharine
since she was three.

484
00:41:41,440 --> 00:41:44,000
We were practically brother and sister
before we were man and wife.

485
00:41:44,080 --> 00:41:46,389
I think I'd know what is and what isn't
too much for her.

486
00:41:46,480 --> 00:41:49,153
I think
she'd know herself.

487
00:41:49,280 --> 00:41:51,077
Very well.

488
00:41:51,200 --> 00:41:53,953
Why are you people
so threatened by a woman ?

489
00:42:04,360 --> 00:42:06,749
// [ Piano ]

490
00:42:30,320 --> 00:42:32,151
[ Tapping ]

491
00:42:34,920 --> 00:42:36,990
I have come to love...

492
00:42:37,080 --> 00:42:40,675
that little tap of the
fingernail against the syringe.

493
00:42:41,760 --> 00:42:44,354
Tap.

494
00:42:44,440 --> 00:42:47,159
Tap.

495
00:42:47,280 --> 00:42:49,077
Tap.

496
00:42:49,200 --> 00:42:52,670
// [ Continues ]

497
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:12,436
- [ Gunshot ]
- Stop playing ! Please, stop playing.

498
00:43:16,960 --> 00:43:19,713
I don't have the key
to that door. You--

499
00:43:22,600 --> 00:43:25,672
The Germans were here.
The Germans were all over this area.

500
00:43:25,800 --> 00:43:28,109
They left mines
everywhere.

501
00:43:28,240 --> 00:43:30,595
The pianos were their
favourite hiding places.

502
00:43:30,680 --> 00:43:32,989
I see.
Sorry.

503
00:43:38,120 --> 00:43:41,635
Then maybe you're safe
as long as you only play Bach.

504
00:43:43,120 --> 00:43:45,190
He's German.

505
00:43:46,360 --> 00:43:48,954
Is something funny ?

506
00:43:49,040 --> 00:43:51,270
No. I'm sorry.

507
00:44:05,360 --> 00:44:07,510
I've met you before.

508
00:44:07,600 --> 00:44:10,910
I don't think so.

509
00:44:20,840 --> 00:44:22,671
Look. See ?

510
00:44:22,800 --> 00:44:25,633
Move that,
and no more Bach.

511
00:44:25,760 --> 00:44:28,991
Lieutenant !
Are you all right, Sir ?

512
00:44:29,080 --> 00:44:31,389
Fine, Sergeant.

513
00:44:31,520 --> 00:44:33,317
So you're working
with the ltalians.

514
00:44:33,440 --> 00:44:35,396
Yeah, trying to get them
to give up their weapons.

515
00:44:35,520 --> 00:44:38,080
I was a thief, so the army
thought I'd be good at it.

516
00:44:38,160 --> 00:44:40,435
I like the ltalians.

517
00:44:40,560 --> 00:44:42,710
[ Hana ]
He wants us to move out.

518
00:44:42,800 --> 00:44:46,110
He says there could be
50 more mines in the building.

519
00:44:46,200 --> 00:44:50,398
[ Hana ] He thinks I'm mad
because I laugh at him.

520
00:44:50,480 --> 00:44:53,313
He's lndian.

521
00:44:53,400 --> 00:44:57,075
- He wears a turban.
- No, he's Sikh.

522
00:44:57,200 --> 00:44:59,475
If he wears a turban,
he's Sikh.

523
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:01,477
I'll probably marry him.

524
00:45:01,560 --> 00:45:04,632
Really ?
That's sudden.

525
00:45:04,720 --> 00:45:06,597
My mother
always told me...

526
00:45:06,720 --> 00:45:10,269
I would summon my husband
by playing the piano.

527
00:45:11,720 --> 00:45:14,473
[ Breathing Heavily ]

528
00:45:16,240 --> 00:45:19,994
- I liked it better when
there were just the two of us.
- Why ? ls he staying ?

529
00:45:20,080 --> 00:45:22,674
With his sergeant,
a Mr Hardy.

530
00:45:24,040 --> 00:45:27,794
We should charge.
Doesn't anyone have a job to do ?

531
00:45:27,920 --> 00:45:31,629
They have to clear all the roads
of mines. That's a big job.

532
00:45:31,760 --> 00:45:34,752
In that case, l--
I suppose we can't charge.

533
00:45:34,880 --> 00:45:37,235
No, we can't.

534
00:45:40,040 --> 00:45:42,315
Thank you.

535
00:45:45,920 --> 00:45:48,673
[ Engines Drone ]

536
00:46:07,640 --> 00:46:11,997
[ Muttering Song Lyrics ]

537
00:46:20,520 --> 00:46:22,795
/ Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy /

538
00:46:22,920 --> 00:46:27,436
// [ Humming ]

539
00:46:27,560 --> 00:46:30,120
/ Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy /

540
00:46:30,200 --> 00:46:32,589
/ Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy /

541
00:46:32,720 --> 00:46:36,838
I've been thinking. How does someone
like you decide to come to the desert ?

542
00:46:36,920 --> 00:46:38,751
What is it ? You--

543
00:46:38,840 --> 00:46:41,957
You're doing whatever you're doing in
your castle, or wherever it is you live,

544
00:46:42,040 --> 00:46:45,476
and one day you say,
"I have to get to the desert," or what ?

545
00:46:45,600 --> 00:46:50,116
I once travelled with a guide
who was taking me to Faya.

546
00:46:50,240 --> 00:46:53,915
He didn't speak
for nine hours.

547
00:46:56,360 --> 00:47:00,797
At the end of it, he pointed
at the horizon and said, "Faya."

548
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:03,713
That was a good day.

549
00:47:13,960 --> 00:47:16,349
Actually, you sing.

550
00:47:18,160 --> 00:47:20,515
- What ?
- You sing.

551
00:47:20,640 --> 00:47:22,949
All the time.

552
00:47:23,080 --> 00:47:25,036
- I do not.
- Ask AI Auf.

553
00:47:26,440 --> 00:47:28,237
AI Auf !

554
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:33,629
- [ Arabic ]
- [ AI Auf Laughs ]

555
00:47:33,720 --> 00:47:36,996
[ Arabic ]

556
00:47:37,080 --> 00:47:39,640
[ AI Auf Singing ]

557
00:47:39,760 --> 00:47:42,558
[ Katharine ] / You'd better be ready
about half past 8:00 /

558
00:47:42,640 --> 00:47:44,756
/ Remember, honey
Don't be late /

559
00:47:44,880 --> 00:47:48,429
/ 'Cause I'll be there
when the band starts playing /

560
00:47:48,560 --> 00:47:50,437
/ Gonna dance off
both my shoes /

561
00:47:50,560 --> 00:47:52,790
/ When they play
the jelly roll blues /

562
00:47:52,880 --> 00:47:57,431
/ Tomorrow night at the
dark-town strutter's ball //

563
00:47:57,520 --> 00:48:00,637
[ AI Auf Singing ]

564
00:48:00,720 --> 00:48:04,679
[ Chanting ln Arabic ]

565
00:48:06,480 --> 00:48:09,392
[ Chanting Continues ]

566
00:48:09,520 --> 00:48:11,954
Give me your hand.

567
00:48:13,840 --> 00:48:15,637
Thanks.

568
00:48:15,760 --> 00:48:19,878
[ Chanting Continues ]

569
00:48:23,520 --> 00:48:26,751
[ Chanting Response ]

570
00:48:30,800 --> 00:48:33,758
[ Chanting Continues ]

571
00:49:47,840 --> 00:49:50,434
Madox !

572
00:49:50,560 --> 00:49:52,471
Madox !

573
00:49:52,560 --> 00:49:54,391
Madox !

574
00:49:54,480 --> 00:49:57,677
- Come quickly ! I've found something !
- What is it ?

575
00:49:57,800 --> 00:50:01,509
D'Ag ! Bermann !
Quick !

576
00:50:18,120 --> 00:50:19,997
My God.

577
00:50:21,680 --> 00:50:23,796
They're swimming.

578
00:50:28,680 --> 00:50:30,955
[ Madox ]
They're swimming.

579
00:50:44,920 --> 00:50:48,196
[ Man Talking: lndistinct ]

580
00:50:49,800 --> 00:50:53,793
[ Men Speaking Arabic ]

581
00:50:58,560 --> 00:51:00,516
Ow !

582
00:51:03,280 --> 00:51:06,431
- You okay ?
- Yeah.

583
00:51:25,880 --> 00:51:26,915
[ Giggling ]

584
00:51:30,880 --> 00:51:32,916
How do you explain...

585
00:51:33,040 --> 00:51:36,157
to someone who has
never been here,

586
00:51:36,240 --> 00:51:40,552
feelings which seem
quite normal ?

587
00:51:43,560 --> 00:51:46,711
I don't know,
my friend.

588
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:49,189
I don't know.

589
00:51:52,560 --> 00:51:54,755
- Aaah !
- Kamal !

590
00:51:54,840 --> 00:51:56,831
Bermann,
what are you doing ?

591
00:51:56,920 --> 00:51:58,911
Bermann !

592
00:52:00,720 --> 00:52:02,756
Watch out !
Watch out !

593
00:52:04,600 --> 00:52:08,195
[ Men Shouting ln Arabic ]

594
00:52:12,200 --> 00:52:15,476
- Get them out of the car !
- Let me help !

595
00:52:15,600 --> 00:52:17,795
Almasy,
are you all right ?

596
00:52:17,880 --> 00:52:20,758
Yes, yes,
I'm fine.

597
00:52:22,400 --> 00:52:25,278
My wrist !
Ah !

598
00:52:25,360 --> 00:52:28,989
[ Men Speaking Arabic ]

599
00:52:38,480 --> 00:52:43,031
I'll be back as quick as I can,
36 hours at the outside.

600
00:52:43,120 --> 00:52:45,270
Try to get
an additional radiator.

601
00:52:45,360 --> 00:52:50,036
We can store it between here
and Pottery Hill. And a better jack.

602
00:52:50,160 --> 00:52:53,391
- We planned badly.
- Bermann ?

603
00:52:54,680 --> 00:52:57,478
[ Engine Starts ]

604
00:52:57,560 --> 00:53:00,028
[ Arabic ]

605
00:53:06,360 --> 00:53:08,112
Safe journey.

606
00:53:10,800 --> 00:53:12,756
Now what ?

607
00:53:12,880 --> 00:53:15,872
[ Madox ] Let's get all
this stuff off.

608
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:18,833
- I'll stay behind, of course.
- Certainly not.

609
00:53:18,960 --> 00:53:21,713
- I caused the problem. I shall stay.
- You can't. None of you can.

610
00:53:21,840 --> 00:53:24,513
No, I insist. There clearly
isn't room for all of us.

611
00:53:24,600 --> 00:53:27,398
I'm the least able to dig, and I'm not
one of the walking wounded.

612
00:53:27,520 --> 00:53:29,317
It's only one night.

613
00:53:29,440 --> 00:53:32,671
If I remain, it's the most effective
method of persuading my husband...

614
00:53:32,800 --> 00:53:36,031
to abandon whatever he's doing
and come and rescue us.

615
00:53:36,160 --> 00:53:38,594
- All right.
- Come on, let's get going.

616
00:53:41,040 --> 00:53:43,508
[ Engine Starts ]

617
00:54:21,080 --> 00:54:24,277
I thought you might like to
paste them into your book.

618
00:54:30,800 --> 00:54:33,155
Well, we--

619
00:54:33,240 --> 00:54:35,549
We took
photographs.

620
00:54:37,720 --> 00:54:39,870
There's no need.

621
00:54:41,040 --> 00:54:43,474
No, really.
I'd like you to have them.

622
00:54:43,600 --> 00:54:45,909
Well, there's really no need.
This is, um--

623
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:49,629
This is just a scrapbook.
They are too good.

624
00:54:49,720 --> 00:54:53,235
I should feel obliged.
Thank you.

625
00:55:07,360 --> 00:55:10,352
And that would be unconscionable,
I suppose, wouldn't it ?

626
00:55:10,480 --> 00:55:12,869
To feel any obligation.

627
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:18,753
Yes, of course it would.

628
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:39,678
[ Men Speaking Arabic ]

629
00:55:47,080 --> 00:55:49,469
You should come
into the shelter.

630
00:55:49,560 --> 00:55:51,437
I'm quite all right,
thank you.

631
00:55:51,560 --> 00:55:55,235
- Look over there.
- What am I looking at ?

632
00:55:55,320 --> 00:55:57,550
Do you see what's happening to them,
the stars ?

633
00:55:57,680 --> 00:56:00,990
- They're so untidy.
I was trying to rearrange them.
- No, no.

634
00:56:01,080 --> 00:56:02,911
Over there.

635
00:56:06,800 --> 00:56:09,268
In a few minutes,
there'll be no stars.

636
00:56:09,360 --> 00:56:11,590
The air
is filling with sand.

637
00:56:17,840 --> 00:56:21,230
[ Wind Howling ]

638
00:56:29,840 --> 00:56:32,752
[ Shouting ]

639
00:57:04,320 --> 00:57:06,276
[ Panting ]

640
00:57:06,400 --> 00:57:09,073
[ Coughing ]

641
00:57:12,200 --> 00:57:15,636
- This is not very good, is it ?
- No.

642
00:57:17,040 --> 00:57:18,837
[ Coughing ]

643
00:57:18,960 --> 00:57:22,430
- We will be all right ?
- Yes.

644
00:57:22,560 --> 00:57:24,357
Yes.

645
00:57:25,320 --> 00:57:27,436
Absolutely.

646
00:57:27,560 --> 00:57:30,757
"Yes" is a comfort.
"Absolutely" is not.

647
00:57:46,280 --> 00:57:49,477
Let me tell you
about winds.

648
00:57:49,560 --> 00:57:52,279
There is a, a whirlwind
from southern Morocco,

649
00:57:52,400 --> 00:57:54,516
the Aajej,

650
00:57:54,640 --> 00:57:58,189
against which the Fellahin
defend themselves with knives.

651
00:57:59,920 --> 00:58:03,629
And there is a,
a Ghibli from Tunis.

652
00:58:03,760 --> 00:58:05,955
- A Ghibli ?
- A Ghibli.

653
00:58:06,040 --> 00:58:09,635
Which rolls and rolls
and rolls and produces a--

654
00:58:09,720 --> 00:58:12,996
- a rather strange nervous condition.
- [ Laughing ]

655
00:58:15,120 --> 00:58:18,954
And then there is the,
the Harmatten,

656
00:58:19,080 --> 00:58:23,631
a red wind, which mariners called
"a sea of darkness."

657
00:58:24,880 --> 00:58:26,757
And red sand
from this wind...

658
00:58:26,880 --> 00:58:29,633
has flown as far as
the south coast of England,

659
00:58:29,720 --> 00:58:32,029
apparently
producing...

660
00:58:32,120 --> 00:58:35,351
showers so dense that they were
mistaken for blood.

661
00:58:35,440 --> 00:58:38,079
Fiction !

662
00:58:38,160 --> 00:58:41,994
We have a house on that coast
and it has never, never rained blood.

663
00:58:42,120 --> 00:58:44,873
No, it's all true.
Herodotus, your friend.

664
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:47,116
- My friend.
- Your fri--

665
00:58:47,240 --> 00:58:49,674
He writes about it...

666
00:58:49,800 --> 00:58:53,076
and he writes about...

667
00:58:53,200 --> 00:58:56,397
a, a wind, the Simoon,

668
00:58:56,520 --> 00:58:59,080
which a nation thought
was so evil,

669
00:58:59,160 --> 00:59:02,436
they declared war on it
and marched out against it.

670
00:59:03,760 --> 00:59:05,955
In full battle dress.

671
00:59:08,120 --> 00:59:10,839
Their swords raised.

672
00:59:29,840 --> 00:59:34,118
[ Engine Running,
Horn Honking ]

673
00:59:34,200 --> 00:59:37,954
Katharine, Katharine, I need
to get out your side, quickly.

674
00:59:38,040 --> 00:59:40,270
A car !
Let me out !

675
00:59:40,400 --> 00:59:42,994
Of course.
I'm sorry.

676
00:59:43,120 --> 00:59:45,190
Ridiculous
to fall asleep !

677
00:59:45,320 --> 00:59:47,231
Unforgivable !

678
00:59:47,360 --> 00:59:49,635
Damn !
The flare !

679
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:52,831
Stop !
Over here !

680
00:59:52,920 --> 00:59:55,036
- [ Honking ]
- Here !

681
00:59:55,120 --> 00:59:57,475
- Stop !
- [ Honking ]

682
00:59:57,600 --> 01:00:00,592
- Madox !
- [ Flare Gun Fires ]

683
01:00:00,720 --> 01:00:03,871
Madox ! Madox !

684
01:00:16,880 --> 01:00:18,996
Our tracks
have disappeared.

685
01:00:19,120 --> 01:00:22,396
Madox will calculate how many miles.
He'll soon turn around.

686
01:00:27,200 --> 01:00:30,033
Could I ask you,
please, to...

687
01:00:30,160 --> 01:00:33,391
paste your paintings
into my book.

688
01:00:33,520 --> 01:00:35,556
I-- I should like
to have them.

689
01:00:35,640 --> 01:00:37,949
I should be honoured.

690
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:43,552
- [ Muffled Honking ]
- The others !

691
01:00:44,720 --> 01:00:47,075
- Oh, God.
- Quick !

692
01:00:47,200 --> 01:00:49,714
[ Honking Continues ]

693
01:00:51,080 --> 01:00:54,709
Oh, how awful !
Are we going to get them out ?

694
01:00:54,800 --> 01:00:57,394
Quick !
Get the other shovel !

695
01:00:57,520 --> 01:01:00,353
[ Honking Continues ]

696
01:01:00,440 --> 01:01:03,716
Am I a terrible coward
to ask how much water we have left ?

697
01:01:03,800 --> 01:01:07,554
A little in our can. We have, uh, water
in the radiator, which can be drunk.

698
01:01:07,680 --> 01:01:11,673
And, uh, that's not cowardly at all.
It's extremely practical.

699
01:01:11,760 --> 01:01:14,991
We, uh-- Oh, come on !
Come on !

700
01:01:15,120 --> 01:01:18,908
- [ Honking Continues ]
- There's also a plant.

701
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:23,152
I've never seen it,
but I believe you can cut a piece
the size of a heart from this plant,

702
01:01:23,280 --> 01:01:26,511
and the next morning it'll be filled
with a delicious liquid.

703
01:01:26,640 --> 01:01:30,269
Find that plant,
cut out its heart.

704
01:01:30,360 --> 01:01:33,955
[ Honking Continues ]

705
01:01:34,080 --> 01:01:36,833
Here.

706
01:01:39,400 --> 01:01:41,914
[ Men Shouting ]

707
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:44,275
Here's the window.

708
01:01:44,400 --> 01:01:47,153
Clear the glass. I'll clear the door.
Mind your hands.

709
01:01:47,280 --> 01:01:50,158
- [ Shouting ]
- It's okay. We're here.

710
01:01:50,280 --> 01:01:52,669
Come on,
clear it quickly.

711
01:01:52,800 --> 01:01:54,597
[ Shouting ]

712
01:01:54,720 --> 01:01:57,553
Hang on.
Coming.

713
01:02:01,640 --> 01:02:05,474
[ Shouting ln Arabic ]

714
01:02:05,600 --> 01:02:09,513
- I've got it. I've got it.
- Help them out. Here.

715
01:02:27,400 --> 01:02:29,789
[ Arabic ]

716
01:03:16,880 --> 01:03:19,110
Katharine.

717
01:03:23,800 --> 01:03:25,631
Water.

718
01:03:31,640 --> 01:03:34,791
[ Flare Fires, Explodes ]

719
01:03:41,240 --> 01:03:43,390
[ Katharine ]
Geoffrey's not in Cairo.

720
01:03:46,720 --> 01:03:49,393
He's not actually
a buffoon.

721
01:03:49,520 --> 01:03:51,397
The plane wasn't
a wedding present.

722
01:03:51,480 --> 01:03:54,040
It belongs to the
British government.

723
01:03:54,160 --> 01:03:57,311
They want aerial maps
of the whole of North Africa.

724
01:03:57,440 --> 01:04:00,034
So I think
he's in Ethiopia.

725
01:04:02,080 --> 01:04:05,117
In case you're counting
on his sudden appearance.

726
01:04:09,040 --> 01:04:11,508
And the marriage.

727
01:04:11,600 --> 01:04:13,750
Is that a fiction ?

728
01:04:16,160 --> 01:04:18,594
No, the marriage
isn't a fiction.

729
01:04:20,920 --> 01:04:23,354
[ Men Shouting ln Arabic ]

730
01:04:23,440 --> 01:04:26,352
- Oh, thank God.
- [ Shouting Continues ]

731
01:04:26,480 --> 01:04:28,357
Thank God.

732
01:04:28,480 --> 01:04:31,392
Madox.
It's Madox.

733
01:04:31,480 --> 01:04:34,631
[ Shouting ]

734
01:04:36,400 --> 01:04:39,119
Am I K. in your book ?

735
01:04:39,240 --> 01:04:41,356
I think I must be.

736
01:05:03,240 --> 01:05:05,037
[ Man ]
Chapter one.

737
01:05:05,160 --> 01:05:09,551
"He sat in defiance of municipal orders
astride the gun Zamzammah--"

738
01:05:09,680 --> 01:05:13,070
I can't read these words. I can't
read them. They stick in my throat.

739
01:05:13,200 --> 01:05:15,395
[ Almasy ] Because you're
reading it too fast.

740
01:05:15,520 --> 01:05:18,193
- Not at all.
- You have to read Kipling slowly.

741
01:05:18,320 --> 01:05:21,915
The eye is too impatient.
Think about the speed of his pen.

742
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:24,912
What is it ?
"He sat, comma,

743
01:05:25,040 --> 01:05:28,032
"in defiance of
municipal orders, comma,

744
01:05:28,120 --> 01:05:30,918
"astride the gun
Zamzammah...

745
01:05:31,040 --> 01:05:34,589
on her brick--"
What is it ?

746
01:05:34,720 --> 01:05:37,393
"Brick platform, opposite the old
Ajaib-Gher."

747
01:05:37,520 --> 01:05:42,116
"The wonder house, comma,

748
01:05:42,200 --> 01:05:45,636
as the natives called
the Lahore Museum."

749
01:05:45,720 --> 01:05:48,837
It's still there, the cannon,
outside the museum.

750
01:05:48,920 --> 01:05:52,515
Made of metal cups and bowls taken
from every household in the city as tax,

751
01:05:52,600 --> 01:05:54,750
then melted down.

752
01:05:54,880 --> 01:05:58,759
Then later, they fired
the cannon at my people,

753
01:05:58,840 --> 01:06:02,435
comma,
the natives.

754
01:06:02,520 --> 01:06:04,351
Full stop.

755
01:06:04,440 --> 01:06:06,271
[ Slurping ]

756
01:06:06,360 --> 01:06:08,191
What exactly
is it you object to ?

757
01:06:08,280 --> 01:06:11,033
The writer,
or what he's writing about ?

758
01:06:11,120 --> 01:06:14,829
What I really
object to, Uncle,

759
01:06:14,960 --> 01:06:17,076
is your finishing
all my condensed milk.

760
01:06:17,200 --> 01:06:19,953
And the message everywhere in your book,
however slowly I read it,

761
01:06:20,080 --> 01:06:23,038
that the best thing for lndia
is to be ruled by the British.

762
01:06:23,120 --> 01:06:26,317
Hana, we have discovered
a shared pleasure, the boy and l.

763
01:06:26,440 --> 01:06:28,829
- Arguing about books ?
- Condensed milk.

764
01:06:28,960 --> 01:06:31,076
One of the truly
great inventions.

765
01:06:31,160 --> 01:06:33,913
I'll get
another tin.

766
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:37,470
I didn't like that book either.
It's all about men.

767
01:06:37,560 --> 01:06:40,836
Too many men.
Just like this house.

768
01:06:40,960 --> 01:06:44,191
You like him, don't you ?
Your voice changes.

769
01:06:44,320 --> 01:06:46,595
No, I don't
think it does.

770
01:06:46,720 --> 01:06:49,075
Anyway,
he's indifferent to me.

771
01:06:49,200 --> 01:06:52,158
I don't think
it's indifference.

772
01:06:52,240 --> 01:06:54,595
- Hana was just telling me,
you're indifferent...
- Hey !

773
01:06:54,720 --> 01:06:56,676
to her cooking.

774
01:06:58,160 --> 01:07:00,037
Well, I'm indifferent
to cooking.

775
01:07:00,120 --> 01:07:02,759
Not Hana's cooking
in particular.

776
01:07:02,880 --> 01:07:05,952
Have either of you tried
condensed milk sandwiches ?

777
01:07:06,080 --> 01:07:07,877
[ Coughing ]

778
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:10,753
They're very good
with salt.

779
01:07:10,840 --> 01:07:14,515
[ Horns Honking ]

780
01:07:14,640 --> 01:07:17,313
[ People Chattering ]

781
01:07:17,400 --> 01:07:19,868
[ Honking ]

782
01:07:30,480 --> 01:07:32,630
Welcome back,
Madam.

783
01:07:44,840 --> 01:07:46,717
Will you not come in ?

784
01:07:46,800 --> 01:07:48,916
No.

785
01:07:49,040 --> 01:07:51,873
- I should go home.
- Will you please come in ?

786
01:07:53,080 --> 01:07:54,911
Mrs Clifton.

787
01:07:57,360 --> 01:07:59,828
Don't.

788
01:07:59,920 --> 01:08:01,797
I believe
you still have my book.

789
01:08:17,200 --> 01:08:19,111
Thank you.

790
01:08:30,320 --> 01:08:33,073
[ Chanting ln Distance ]

791
01:08:38,120 --> 01:08:40,076
[ Knocking ]

792
01:08:43,800 --> 01:08:45,631
[ Knocking ]

793
01:08:52,720 --> 01:08:54,676
[ Hinges Creak ]

794
01:09:39,920 --> 01:09:42,673
You still have
sand in your hair.

795
01:10:05,200 --> 01:10:07,953
/ It wouldn't be
make believe /

796
01:10:08,080 --> 01:10:11,277
/ lf you believe in me /

797
01:10:11,400 --> 01:10:14,710
/ Without your love /

798
01:10:14,800 --> 01:10:17,030
I'm impressed
you can sew.

799
01:10:17,160 --> 01:10:18,957
Good.

800
01:10:25,800 --> 01:10:28,268
You sew very badly.

801
01:10:28,400 --> 01:10:30,595
Well, you don't
sew at all.

802
01:10:30,680 --> 01:10:32,511
A woman should
never learn to sew,

803
01:10:32,600 --> 01:10:35,068
and if she can,
she shouldn't admit to it.

804
01:10:35,160 --> 01:10:37,151
[ Snickers ]

805
01:10:42,560 --> 01:10:45,438
Close your eyes.

806
01:10:45,520 --> 01:10:48,398
It makes it harder still.

807
01:10:51,120 --> 01:10:52,951
Hmm.

808
01:10:56,320 --> 01:10:58,436
When were you
most happy ?

809
01:10:58,560 --> 01:11:01,074
Now.

810
01:11:02,480 --> 01:11:04,596
And when were you
least happy ?

811
01:11:07,120 --> 01:11:08,997
Now.

812
01:11:13,760 --> 01:11:16,479
- What do you love ?
- What do I love ?

813
01:11:16,560 --> 01:11:19,438
- Say "everything."
- Let's see.

814
01:11:19,560 --> 01:11:21,516
- Water.
- Mm-hmm.

815
01:11:21,640 --> 01:11:23,676
[ Water Splashing ]

816
01:11:23,760 --> 01:11:26,320
- Fish in it.
- [ Chuckles ]

817
01:11:26,440 --> 01:11:29,159
And hedgehogs.
I love hedgehogs.

818
01:11:29,280 --> 01:11:31,077
And what else ?

819
01:11:31,200 --> 01:11:33,953
Marmite.
I'm addicted.

820
01:11:35,760 --> 01:11:38,832
And baths.
But not with other people.

821
01:11:38,960 --> 01:11:41,076
[ Laughing ]

822
01:11:43,400 --> 01:11:45,311
Islands.

823
01:11:47,400 --> 01:11:49,675
And your handwriting.

824
01:11:51,600 --> 01:11:54,478
- Mmm.
- I could go on all day.

825
01:11:54,600 --> 01:11:56,477
Go on all day.

826
01:12:04,200 --> 01:12:06,395
My husband.

827
01:12:08,280 --> 01:12:10,589
And what do you
hate most ?

828
01:12:14,120 --> 01:12:16,236
A lie.

829
01:12:17,520 --> 01:12:20,557
What do you
hate most ?

830
01:12:23,720 --> 01:12:26,154
Ownership.

831
01:12:26,280 --> 01:12:28,236
Being owned.

832
01:12:29,400 --> 01:12:32,039
When you leave,
you should forget me.

833
01:13:00,960 --> 01:13:04,060
- [ Hana ] Who is this ?
- [ Almasy ] Don't you recognize me ?

